                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d143">
                <head>143. Telegram 768 from Tegucigalpa, April 21<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d143fn1">President <persName corresp="#p_VMJR_1">Villeda
                            Morales</persName> proposal to break relations with Cuba on April 22.
                        Unclassified. 1 p. <gloss target="#t_DOS_1">DOS</gloss>, <gloss
                            target="#t_CF_1">CF</gloss>, 715.00/4–2161.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Tegucigalpa</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1961-04-21">April 21, 1961</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d143-1" n="1" type="facsimile" xml:id="d143-1"/>
                <p>President <persName corresp="#p_VMJR_1">Villeda Morales</persName> announced
                    tonight to cheering anti-Castro crowd, and over national hookup that he would
                    lay before Council of Ministers his proposal to break relations with Cuba, and
                    that Foreign Ministry would carry out action tomorrow, Saturday, April 22.
                    President’s oratory was strongly and outspokenly anti-Communist, stressed that
                    his action was compliance will of people from whom he had sprung, cautioned that
                    will to abandon extreme left implied equal responsibility to break with plotters
                    of extreme right. Crowd had been warmed by two hours of oratory in main square
                    before marching on Palace to ask for break, obviously with knowledge of
                    authorities. Manifestation contrasted imposingly with failure several
                    Castro-Communist attempts organize rallies. President’s announcement was
                    followed by shooting of fire-arms, a common practice at any celebration, but no
                    disorder as yet.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed corresp="#p_BCR_1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_BCR_1">Burrows</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
